default2.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGeneral commentsdefault&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBSW Timber’s interest in the Housing Standard Review is as a supplier of timber as a building material. Our economic activity is dependent on a thriving construction sector, particularly in house building. We support the Government’s current initiatives to address the UK’s housing shortage. We are firm believers in our product offering a natural and renewable solution as a building component. Timber is a natural sequester of carbon and therefore offers a unique contribution to sustainable solutions. We believe its contribution should be investigated more seriously. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have a concern that in its laudable approach to localism, Government loses its leadership role in driving sustainability standards and efficiency improvements. An appropriate balance is needed.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe support the need for some simplification of housing standards but we are concerned about the potential unintended consequences of a dilution of the progress already made in raising sustainability standards in our housing stock. The planned phasing out of the Code for Sustainable Homes must be counter-balanced by clear intent within new standards that environmental requirements are to be maintained.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe refer to Paragraphs 42, 43 and 44 of the Consultation in which Government expresses concern about the potential proliferation of local standards and supports its proposal to issue a Policy Statement encouraging local authorities to align with local standards. We support this provided that the scope of the standard and policy statement is comprehensive enough to continue the legacy of Code for Sustainable Homes and addresses the key omission of a requirement for responsible sourcing of materials.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe 
defaultsupport UK GBC view that 
defaultsuitable transitional arrangements must be put into place, and where 
defaultLocal Planning Authorities (
defaultLPAs
default)
default already have higher standards in place and developers are meeting those standards without difficulty (e
default.
defaultg
default.
default C
defaultode for Sustainable Homes level
default 4), they should be allowed to keep those higher requirements until the new regulations take over (e
default.
defaultg
default.
default Part L 2016). There is no sense in weakening environmental requirements which are easily being met, only to raise them again in 2-3 years.  
default&#xa0;
