default3.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultChapter 2: Spacedefault&#xa0;default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe support some level of housing space standards to ensure a decent home provision but find the Government’s proscriptive position in this at odds with their stance on materials.
default&#xa0;
default4.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultChapter 3: Energydefault&#xa0;
default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe support UK GBC comments on energy.
default&#xa0;
default5.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultChapter 7: Materialsdefault&#xa0;default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBSW believe that the exclusion of such a key sustainability requirements as materials sourcing is a mistake. 
defaultWe st
defaultrongly disagree with leaving considerations about m
defaultaterials to the market
default and EU Policy
default. This is perhaps the biggest omission in the
default proposed new Housing Standards. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIssue
defaults such as
default responsible sourcing, toxicity, Ozone depleting potential, and off-gassing of materials in air-tight homes should not be left to the market but should be addressed as a matter of urgency through new guidance and regulation.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMuch improvement has been made in the sustainability of products both through reducing impact and responsibly sourcing but manufacturers and suppliers can continue to respond to the sustainability agenda if the Government maintains an active interest in this area rather than leaving it to the market.
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGreat progress has been made with sustainable and renewable or recyclable building materials such as timber and wood composite products which could make a valuable contribution to the UK’s 2016 zero carbon homes target. The Government has an opportunity to provide leadership to local authorities, planners and developers in meeting this target by taking forward work on embodied energy standards. We strongly recommend that the Government establish a working party to advise Government on drafting new guidelines for material standards for new homes.
default&#xa0;
default6.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConclusiondefault&#xa0;
defaultWe believe that the omission of material standards from the Housing Standards Review is a mistake and presents a lost opportunity for the zero carbon agenda. We very much hope that the committee will want to robustly examine this aspect of the Government’s recommendations within the consultation. We believe that the time is right to take forward the embodied energy standards agenda to create a clearer understanding and evidence of what works. BSW would welcome the opportunity to supply further oral evidence to the committee. 
default3 October 2013
